{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516886"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.37,0.04,0.42,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39767"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44961"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"39767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/39767"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents with a one week history of persistent ringing in his ears. He is otherwise in good health, apart from pain in his right shoulder which started six weeks ago. He was initially commenced on paracetamol and ibuprofen for the pain and underwent several weeks of physiotherapy, before being started on codeine suppositories for ongoing pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol","Ibuprofen","Physiotherapy","Codeine","Presbycusis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDS), such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eibuprofen \u003C/strong\u003Ecan cause tinnitus when used for prolonged periods of time. The patient in this case presents with tinnitus several weeks after commencing NSAIDs, and no clinical features to suggest an alternative diagnosis are mentioned, thus making ibuprofen the most likely explanation for his symptoms. The tinnitus associated with NSAIDs is often reversible when they are ceased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresbycusis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by sensorineural hearing loss associated with ageing and is a common cause of tinnitus. While presbycusis is a reasonable differential in this patient, there is a clear temporal relationship between starting NSAIDs and the development of symptoms, making it a more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol, physiotherapy, \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Ecodeine\u003C/strong\u003E are routine treatments for nociceptive pain but are not common causes of tinnitus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prolonged use of NSAIDs can cause tinnitus."],"references":["Bauer CA. Tinnitus. N Engl J Med. 2018 Mar 29;378(13):1224-1231. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp1506631. PMID: 29601255."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-07T11:20:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T17:43:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"